children.comment: Everything in Dart is an [Object].
children.name: Object

children.comment:
The equality operator.

The default behavior for all [Object]s is to return true if and
only if [:this:] and [other] are the same object.

If a subclass overrides the equality operator it should override
the [hashCode] method as well to maintain consistency.
Returns a string representation of this object.
children.name: toString

children.comment:
[noSuchMethod] is invoked when users invoke a non-existant method
on an object. The name of the method and the arguments of the
invocation are passed to [noSuchMethod] in an [Invocation].
If [noSuchMethod] returns a value, that value becomes the result of
the original invocation.

The default behavior of [noSuchMethod] is to throw a
[noSuchMethodError].
children.name: noSuchMethod

children.comment:
Get a hash code for this object.

All objects have hash codes. Hash codes are guaranteed to be the
same for objects that are equal when compared using the equality
operator [:==:]. Other than that there are no guarantees about
the hash codes. They will not be consistent between runs and
there are no distribution guarantees.

If a subclass overrides [hashCode] it should override the
equality operator as well to maintain consistency.
children.name: hashCode

children.comment: A representation of the runtime type of the object.
children.name: runtimeType

children.comment:
Creates a new [Object] instance.

[Object] instances have no meaningful state, and are only useful
through their identity. An [Object] instance is equal to itself
only.

The base class for HTTP requests.

Subclasses of [BaseRequest] can be constructed manually and passed to
[BaseClient.send], which allows the user to provide fine-grained control
over the request properties. However, usually it's easier to use convenience
methods like [get] or [BaseClient.get].
children.name: BaseRequest

children.comment:
Finalizes the HTTP request in preparation for it being sent. This freezes
all mutable fields and returns a single-subscription [ByteStream] that
emits the body of the request.

The base implementation of this returns null rather than a [ByteStream];
subclasses are responsible for creating the return value, which should be
single-subscription to ensure that no data is dropped. They should also
freeze any additional mutable fields they add that don't make sense to
change after the request headers are sent.
children.name: finalize

children.comment:
Sends this request.

This automatically initializes a new [Client] and closes that client once
the request is complete. If you're planning on making multiple requests to
the same server, you should use a single [Client] for all of those
requests.
children.name: send

children.comment: Throws an error if this request has been finalized.
children.name: _checkFinalized

children.comment:
The size of the request body, in bytes. This defaults to -1, which
indicates that the size of the request is not known in advance.
children.name: contentLength

children.comment:
Whether a persistent connection should be maintained with the server.
Defaults to true.
children.name: persistentConnection

children.comment:
Whether the client should follow redirects while resolving this request.
Defaults to true.
children.name: followRedirects

children.comment:
The maximum number of redirects to follow when [followRedirects] is true.
If this number is exceeded the [BaseResponse] future will signal a
[RedirectException]. Defaults to 5.
children.name: maxRedirects

children.comment: Whether the request has been finalized.
children.name: finalized

children.comment:
The HTTP method of the request. Most commonly "GET" or "POST", less
commonly "HEAD", "PUT", or "DELETE". Non-standard method names are also
supported.
children.name: method

children.comment: The URL to which the request will be sent.
children.name: url

children.comment: The headers for this request.
children.name: headers

children.comment: Creates a new HTTP request.

children.name: MultipartRequest

children.comment:
Freezes all mutable fields and returns a single-subscription [ByteStream]
that will emit the request body.
children.name: finalize

children.comment:
Returns the header string for a field. The return value is guaranteed to
contain only ASCII characters.
children.name: _headerForField

children.comment:
Returns the header string for a file. The return value is guaranteed to
contain only ASCII characters.
children.name: _headerForFile

children.comment:
Returns a randomly-generated multipart boundary string of the given
[length].
children.name: _boundaryString

children.comment: The list of files to upload for this request.
children.name: files

children.comment:
The total length of the request body, in bytes. This is calculated from
[fields] and [files] and cannot be set manually.
children.name: contentLength

children.comment:
The total length of the multipart boundaries used when building the
request body. According to http://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc1341.html, this
can't be longer than 70.
children.name: _BOUNDARY_LENGTH

children.comment: The form fields to send for this request.
children.name: fields

children.comment: The private version of [files].
children.name: _files

children.comment:
All character codes that are valid in multipart boundaries. From
http://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc2046#section-5.1.1.
children.name: _BOUNDARY_CHARACTERS

children.comment: Creates a new [MultipartRequest].
